const initialSystemDark = getSystemDark();
const initialThemeId = resolveThemeId(initialPreference, initialSystemDark);
applyTheme(initialThemeId);
```

---

### 8. Settings Page Changes

In `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`:

- Remove the `THEME_OPTIONS` constant (lines 25-41)
- Remove the inline Appearance section JSX (lines 202-243)
- Import and render `<ThemeSelector />` in its place
- The `ThemeSelector` receives no props; it calls `useTheme()` internally

---

### 9. ThemeSelector Component Design

`apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`:

```
+------------------------------------------------------+
| Appearance                                           |
| Choose your preferred color theme.                   |
|                                                      |
|  [ System ]  (toggle, when active shows which        |
|               theme it resolves to)                   |
|                                                      |
|  +-------------+ +-------------+ +----------------+  |
|  | T3 Light    | | T3 Dark     | | Midnight       |  |
|  |             | |             | |                |  |
|  | [swatch]    | | [swatch]    | | [swatch]       |  |
|  | ........... | | ........... | | ...............|  |
|  | bg  fg  acc | | bg  fg  acc | | bg   fg   acc  |  |
|  +-------------+ +-------------+ +----------------+  |
|                                                      |
|  Active: T3 Dark                                     |
+------------------------------------------------------+
```

Each theme card shows:
- Theme name
- A mini swatch strip with 4-5 color circles: background, foreground, primary, accent, sidebar-background
- A selected/active indicator (border highlight + badge, matching the current pattern on the settings page)
- Click to select

There is also a "System" toggle at the top. When "System" is selected, the card corresponding to the resolved theme gets a subtle "Auto" badge.

The component structure:

```typescript
function ThemeSelector() {
  const { theme, themeId, setTheme } = useTheme();
  const isSystem = theme === "system";

  return (
    <section className="rounded-2xl border border-border bg-card p-5">
      <div className="mb-4">
        <h2 className="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Appearance</h2>
        <p className="mt-1 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Choose your preferred color theme.
        </p>
      </div>

      {/* System toggle */}
      <div className="mb-4 flex items-center justify-between rounded-lg border border-border bg-background px-3 py-2">
        <div>
          <p className="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Match system</p>
          <p className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
            Automatically switch between light and dark.
          </p>
        </div>
        <Switch
          checked={isSystem}
          onCheckedChange={(checked) => {
            setTheme(checked ? "system" : themeId);
          }}
        />
      </div>

      {/* Theme cards grid */}
      <div className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Color theme">
        {THEME_IDS.map((id) => {
          const def = getThemeDefinition(id);
          const isActive = isSystem ? themeId === id : theme === id;
          return (
            <ThemeCard
              key={id}
              definition={def}
              isActive={isActive}
              isAutoSelected={isSystem && themeId === id}
              onSelect={() => setTheme(isSystem ? "system" : id)}
              disabled={isSystem}
            />
          );
        })}
      </div>

      <p className="mt-4 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
        Active theme: <span className="font-medium text-foreground">
          {getThemeDefinition(themeId).name}
        </span>
        {isSystem ? " (system)" : ""}
      </p>
    </section>
  );
}
```

`ThemeCard` is a local sub-component that renders the swatch strip:

```typescript
function ThemeCard({ definition, isActive, isAutoSelected, onSelect, disabled }) {
  const { colors } = definition;
  const swatchColors = [
    colors.background,
    colors.foreground,
    colors.primary,
    colors["sidebar-background"],
    colors["terminal-background"],
  ];

  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      role="radio"
      aria-checked={isActive}
      disabled={disabled && !isActive}
      className={cn(
        "flex flex-col gap-2 rounded-xl border p-3 text-left transition-colors",
        isActive
          ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8"
          : "border-border bg-background hover:bg-accent",
        disabled && !isActive && "opacity-50 cursor-default"
      )}
      onClick={onSelect}
    >
      <span className="text-xs font-medium">{definition.name}</span>
      <div className="flex gap-1.5">
        {swatchColors.map((color, i) => (
          <span
            key={i}
            className="size-4 rounded-full border border-border/50"
            style={{ backgroundColor: color }}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
      {isActive && (
        <span className="rounded bg-primary/14 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-primary">
          {isAutoSelected ? "Auto" : "Selected"}
        </span>
      )}
    </button>
  );
}
```

---

### 10. localStorage Persistence and Migration

**New key**: `t3code:theme-preference`

**Stored values**: One of `"system"`, `"t3-light"`, `"t3-dark"`, `"t3-midnight"`

**Migration from old key** (`t3code:theme`):

```typescript
function migrateOldThemeKey(): void {
  const OLD_KEY = "t3code:theme";
  const old = localStorage.getItem(OLD_KEY);
  if (old === null) return;

  const MIGRATION_MAP: Record<string, ThemePreference> = {
    system: "system",
    light: "t3-light",
    dark: "t3-dark",
  };

  const migrated = MIGRATION_MAP[old] ?? "system";
  localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, migrated);
  localStorage.removeItem(OLD_KEY);
}
```

This runs once at module load, before `getStored()` is called. After migration, the old key is deleted to prevent re-migration.

**Cross-tab sync** continues to work via the existing `storage` event listener pattern, updated to listen on the new key.

---

### 11. Backward Compatibility with DiffWorkerPoolProvider

`DiffWorkerPoolProvider` at `/apps/web/src/components/DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx` line 32 does:
```typescript
const { resolvedTheme } = useTheme();
const diffThemeName = resolveDiffThemeName(resolvedTheme);
```

`resolveDiffThemeName` maps `"light" | "dark"` to `"pierre-light" | "pierre-dark"`. Since the refactored hook still returns `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"` (derived from `getThemeMode(themeId)`), this code requires zero changes. The same applies to `ChatMarkdown.tsx`, `DiffPanel.tsx`, and `ChatView.tsx` -- they all destructure only `{ resolvedTheme }`.

The `ChatView.tsx` also passes `resolvedTheme` as a prop typed `"light" | "dark"` to sub-components (`ComposerCommandMenuItem`, `MessagesTimeline`, `TurnDiffFileTree`). These all continue to work because the type is preserved.

---

### 12. Implementation Sequence

**Phase 1 -- Schema and shared layer (no UI changes)**
1. Create `packages/contracts/src/theme.ts` with `ThemeId`, `ThemeMode`, `ThemePreference` schemas
2. Add re-export to `packages/contracts/src/index.ts`
3. Create `packages/shared/src/theme.ts` with `ThemeColors`, `ThemeDefinition`, `BUILT_IN_THEMES`, helper functions
4. Add `"./theme"` subpath to `packages/shared/package.json`

**Phase 2 -- CSS foundation**
5. Add new CSS custom properties to `apps/web/src/index.css` (`:root`, `@variant dark`, `@theme inline` blocks)

**Phase 3 -- Hook refactoring**
6. Refactor `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`:
   - Add migration logic
   - Change snapshot to use `ThemePreference`
   - Implement `applyTheme` with CSS property iteration
   - Preserve `resolvedTheme` in return value
   - Keep module-level initialization pattern

**Phase 4 -- UI**
7. Create `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`
8. Update `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` to use `ThemeSelector`

---

### 13. Potential Challenges and Mitigations

1. **oklch values in setProperty**: The existing CSS uses `oklch(0.488 0.217 264)` and `color-mix(...)` for some values. When these are set via `style.setProperty`, they work in modern browsers but not in older ones. Mitigation: The t3-light and t3-dark themes use hex fallbacks for computed values, while the midnight theme uses only hex/rgba values. The `oklch` values in t3-light/t3-dark match what the CSS already uses, so browser support is identical.

2. **Tailwind `var()` references in CSS**: The existing `:root` block uses Tailwind's `var(--color-white)`, `var(--color-neutral-800)` etc. which are Tailwind v4 theme tokens. When we override via `style.setProperty`, we use resolved hex values instead, which is correct because inline styles take precedence. The CSS-level `:root` definitions remain as the "no JS" fallback.

3. **`--alpha()` function in CSS**: The existing CSS uses `--alpha(var(--color-black) / 4%)` which is a Tailwind v4 specific function. The runtime overrides use standard `rgba()` equivalents, which is the correct approach since `style.setProperty` deals in standard CSS.

4. **Sidebar color resolution**: The existing `sidebar.tsx` uses classes like `bg-sidebar` and `text-sidebar-foreground`. In Tailwind v4, `bg-sidebar` resolves to `--color-sidebar`. We need to ensure the `@theme inline` block maps `--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar-background)` (not `--color-sidebar-background`). The shadcn convention is `bg-sidebar` -> `--color-sidebar`, so the theme inline mapping is:
   ```css
   --color-sidebar: var(--sidebar-background);
   --color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground);
   /* etc. */
   ```

5. **Flash of unstyled content**: The module-level `applyTheme()` call at import time handles this, same as the current system. Since the hook file is imported early (via route components), the CSS properties are set before first paint.

